Observation Details: 1 juvenile

Multiple individuals seen coming down to beg for peanuts. Combination of varying molt states and at different areas. Expected up here. Photos, will upload  Post hike update; the first bird we saw (all attached photos from that encounter) came in silently and was spotted by Simone at which point we fed it a few crumbs of granola bar in typical Canada Jay fashion. What happened when we stopped feeding it however was that it dropped down to a patch of white slime mold which we previously hadn't noticed and began collecting globs of it in its beak and flying off to a nearby tree where it cached the slime mold in a piece of outhanging bark. We were pretty interested as neither of us had ever seen any bird interacting with slime mold so took a few photos of the event as well as climbed down to the slime mold to take a closer picture once the bird had finished and flown off. It made this short journey maybe 3 times before it departed and was not seen again.  Interested by the interaction I checked Birds of the World the following day and found a paper citing this behaviour from 1979 (see citation below). I also sent a few photos off to Dan Strickland who studies Canada Jay nearby on Strathcona to see if he might be interested. Much to my surprise he responded in less than an hour stating that to his knowledge this was only the third ever recorded instance of Canada Jay feeding on slime mould, the first being the paper cited above, and the second being a paper published a month and a day before this sighting in which Dan himself recorded slime mould residue on the bill of a bird at Strathcona and worked with a slime mould specialist to confirm it as Fuligo septica, the same species of slime mould described from the 1979 paper. He also asked if he could pass the photos of the slime mould on to Loys Maingon to see if they could confirm the species, as it didn't look like F. septica. Loys unfortunately said that as the slime mould was not in its reproductive stage it was impossible to confirm the species ID, though suggested it could be a pale morph F. septica.  One final note on the encounter; talking to Ann Nightingale a week later she noted that my assumption of the bird stashing the slime mould for food may not be correct, and that hypothetically it could be using the slime mould to innoculate existing stashes of food against bacteria and other agents which might cause it to spoil.  All in all, super cool sighting and subsequent discussion! Feeling incredibly grateful to be apart of such an informed and inquisitive community of naturalists willing to pry into obscure and odd behaviours.  Second follow up update; I now understand from Dan Strickland that these were some of if not the first photos ever taken of a Canada Jay actively caching food, which is hard to conceive of. Would love to hear of more instances / photos if anyone knows of any.  1. Sutherland, J. B. and R. L. Crawford. (1979). Gray Jay feeding on slime mold. Murrelet 60:28.  2. Sutton AO, Strickland D, Lachapelle J, Young RG, Hanner R, Brunton DF, et al. (2024) Fecal DNA metabarcoding helps characterize the Canada jay’s diet and confirms its reliance on stored food for winter survival and breeding. PLoS ONE 19(4): e0300583. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0300583)  3. Slime mould from Arrowsmith: https://inaturalist.ca/observations/218394250

Multiple individuals seen coming down to beg for peanuts. Combination of varying molt states and at different areas. Expected up here. Photos, will upload  Post hike update; the first bird we saw (all attached photos from that encounter) came in silently and was spotted by Simone at which point we fed it a few crumbs of granola bar in typical Canada Jay fashion. What happened when we stopped feeding it however was that it dropped down to a patch of white slime mold which we previously hadn't noticed and began collecting globs of it in its beak and flying off to a nearby tree where it cached the slime mold in a piece of outhanging bark. We were pretty interested as neither of us had ever seen any bird interacting with slime mold so took a few photos of the event as well as climbed down to the slime mold to take a closer picture once the bird had finished and flown off. It made this short journey maybe 3 times before it departed and was not seen again.  Interested by the interaction I checked Birds of the World the following day and found a paper citing this behaviour from 1979 (see citation below). I also sent a few photos off to Dan Strickland who studies Canada Jay nearby on Strathcona to see if he might be interested. Much to my surprise he responded in less than an hour stating that to his knowledge this was only the third ever recorded instance of Canada Jay feeding on slime mould, the first being the paper cited above, and the second being a paper published a month and a day before this sighting in which Dan himself recorded slime mould residue on the bill of a bird at Strathcona and worked with a slime mould specialist to confirm it as Fuligo septica, the same species of slime mould described from the 1979 paper. He also asked if he could pass the photos of the slime mould on to Loys Maingon to see if they could confirm the species, as it didn't look like F. septica. Loys unfortunately said that as the slime mould was not in its reproductive stage it was impossible to confirm the species ID, though suggested it could be a pale morph F. septica.  One final note on the encounter; talking to Ann Nightingale a week later she noted that my assumption of the bird stashing the slime mould for food may not be correct, and that hypothetically it could be using the slime mould to innoculate existing stashes of food against bacteria and other agents which might cause it to spoil.  All in all, super cool sighting and subsequent discussion! Feeling incredibly grateful to be apart of such an informed and inquisitive community of naturalists willing to pry into obscure and odd behaviours.  Second follow up update; I now understand from Dan Strickland that these were some of if not the first photos ever taken of a Canada Jay actively caching food, which is hard to conceive of. Would love to hear of more instances / photos if anyone knows of any.  1. Sutherland, J. B. and R. L. Crawford. (1979). Gray Jay feeding on slime mold. Murrelet 60:28.  2. Sutton AO, Strickland D, Lachapelle J, Young RG, Hanner R, Brunton DF, et al. (2024) Fecal DNA metabarcoding helps characterize the Canada jay’s diet and confirms its reliance on stored food for winter survival and breeding. PLoS ONE 19(4): e0300583. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0300583)  3. Slime mould from Arrowsmith: https://inaturalist.ca/observations/218394250

Locality: Dixville Turbines to Rt. 26 via West Branch Clear Stream Rd.

Observation Details: Multiple individuals seen coming down to beg for peanuts. Combination of varying molt states and at different areas. Expected up here. Photos, will upload  Post hike update; the first bird we saw (all attached photos from that encounter) came in silently and was spotted by Simone at which point we fed it a few crumbs of granola bar in typical Canada Jay fashion. What happened when we stopped feeding it however was that it dropped down to a patch of white slime mold which we previously hadn't noticed and began collecting globs of it in its beak and flying off to a nearby tree where it cached the slime mold in a piece of outhanging bark. We were pretty interested as neither of us had ever seen any bird interacting with slime mold so took a few photos of the event as well as climbed down to the slime mold to take a closer picture once the bird had finished and flown off. It made this short journey maybe 3 times before it departed and was not seen again.  Interested by the interaction I checked Birds of the World the following day and found a paper citing this behaviour from 1979 (see citation below). I also sent a few photos off to Dan Strickland who studies Canada Jay nearby on Strathcona to see if he might be interested. Much to my surprise he responded in less than an hour stating that to his knowledge this was only the third ever recorded instance of Canada Jay feeding on slime mould, the first being the paper cited above, and the second being a paper published a month and a day before this sighting in which Dan himself recorded slime mould residue on the bill of a bird at Strathcona and worked with a slime mould specialist to confirm it as Fuligo septica, the same species of slime mould described from the 1979 paper. He also asked if he could pass the photos of the slime mould on to Loys Maingon to see if they could confirm the species, as it didn't look like F. septica. Loys unfortunately said that as the slime mould was not in its reproductive stage it was impossible to confirm the species ID, though suggested it could be a pale morph F. septica.  One final note on the encounter; talking to Ann Nightingale a week later she noted that my assumption of the bird stashing the slime mould for food may not be correct, and that hypothetically it could be using the slime mould to innoculate existing stashes of food against bacteria and other agents which might cause it to spoil.  All in all, super cool sighting and subsequent discussion! Feeling incredibly grateful to be apart of such an informed and inquisitive community of naturalists willing to pry into obscure and odd behaviours.  Second follow up update; I now understand from Dan Strickland that these were some of if not the first photos ever taken of a Canada Jay actively caching food, which is hard to conceive of. Would love to hear of more instances / photos if anyone knows of any.  1. Sutherland, J. B. and R. L. Crawford. (1979). Gray Jay feeding on slime mold. Murrelet 60:28.  2. Sutton AO, Strickland D, Lachapelle J, Young RG, Hanner R, Brunton DF, et al. (2024) Fecal DNA metabarcoding helps characterize the Canada jay’s diet and confirms its reliance on stored food for winter survival and breeding. PLoS ONE 19(4): e0300583. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0300583)  3. Slime mould from Arrowsmith: https://inaturalist.ca/observations/218394250

Locality: Grand Teton NP--Colter Bay--Hermitage Point Trail

Observation Details: Screenshots from an iPhone video included

Appeared to be two possible separate groups as one group was around 1.5 miles south which quickly showed up for cashews. These fed for a bit before another group came in from the north and the two groups fought over cashews. All of these birds remained active along a 1.5 mile stretch of the northern part of the trail, and were busy eating some bread somebody had left on the feeding platform at about 3 PM.   Gave a wide variety of calls, including a 2-note descending call that sounded similar to a car alarm given by one bird to bring in the rest for food; accipiter-like calls; mimicking Blue Jays; squeaky calls that sounded exactly like two trees rubbing against each other in the wind; and when one attacked a Blue Jay it made sounds like an annoyed budgie or cockatiel.

Each pair I observed, on different parts of the trail, were chasing one another, playfully, perhaps a courtship display, and then seemed curious when they noted our presence and perched above as if to observe us. The first pair watched us for a while, and then resumed searching for and eating spiders in the lichen on the tree branches. The second pair, later in the morning, seemed to be following us along the trail. All were very noisy such that I heard them throughout two long days of hiking and birding, and saw both sets in the same areas on the second day. There may have been more, but I'm only certain that I observed 4 separate ones, each in what appeared to be a mated pair.

What happened when we stopped feeding it however was that it dropped down to a patch of white slime mold which we previously hadn't noticed and began collecting globs of it in its beak and flying off to a nearby tree where it cached the slime mold in a piece of outhanging bark. We were pretty interested as neither of us had ever seen any bird interacting with slime mold so took a few photos of the event as well as climbed down to the slime mold to take a closer picture once the bird had finished and flown off. It made this short journey maybe 3 times before it departed and was not seen again.  Interested by the interaction I checked Birds of the World the following day and found a paper citing this behaviour from 1979 (see citation below). I also sent a few photos off to Dan Strickland who studies Canada Jay nearby on Strathcona to see if he might be interested. Much to my surprise he responded in less than an hour stating that to his knowledge this was only the third ever recorded instance of Canada Jay feeding on slime mould, the first being the paper cited above, and the second being a paper published a month and a day before this sighting in which Dan himself recorded slime mould residue on the bill of a bird at Strathcona and worked with a slime mould specialist to confirm it as Fuligo septica, the same species of slime mould described from the 1979 paper. He also asked if he could pass the photos of the slime mould on to Loys Maingon to see if they could confirm the species, as it didn't look like F. septica. Loys unfortunately said that as the slime mould was not in its reproductive stage it was impossible to confirm the species ID, though suggested it could be a pale morph F. septica.  One final note on the encounter; talking to Ann Nightingale a week later she noted that my assumption of the bird stashing the slime mould for food may not be correct, and that hypothetically it could be using the slime mould to innoculate existing stashes of food against bacteria and other agents which might cause it to spoil.  All in all, super cool sighting and subsequent discussion! Feeling incredibly grateful to be apart of such an informed and inquisitive community of naturalists willing to pry into obscure and odd behaviours.  Second follow up update; I now understand from Dan Strickland that these were some of if not the first photos ever taken of a Canada Jay actively caching food, which is hard to conceive of. Would love to hear of more instances / photos if anyone knows of any.  1. Sutherland, J. B. and R. L. Crawford. (1979). Gray Jay feeding on slime mold. Murrelet 60:28.  2. Sutton AO, Strickland D, Lachapelle J, Young RG, Hanner R, Brunton DF, et al. (2024) Fecal DNA metabarcoding helps characterize the Canada jay’s diet and confirms its reliance on stored food for winter survival and breeding. PLoS ONE 19(4): e0300583. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0300583)  3. Slime mould from Arrowsmith: https://inaturalist.ca/observations/218394250

Soon it flew down and landed on my height some 10 feet away and started cheeping at me, and was joined by another one. Clearly they were asking for food. I had a snack with me, so I broke it into small piece and held it on on my hand. One bird flew in, landed for 2 seconds on my hand, picked up the food and flew back to its perch. Soon the second one did the same and 4 more birds showed up and got their share.

Observation Details: At least 5, maybe 6 birds passed by from SW to NE. They moved surprisingly fast and the light wasn't very good so I wasn't able to age every individual. At least 2 were juveniles and 1 adult but the other 2-3 escaped me. The juveniles were molting toward adult plumage, leaving a very chickadee-like head pattern. It's possible this was one family group but I kinda wondered it it was two families now moving together. Who knows, but cool to see as this species continues to decline from all but the best bogs like this one.

Birded south on the PCT to the meadow without finding GrJa. On the way back up the trail, two  GrJa passed through high in the forest. As we moved up higher a single bird landed low in a tree ahead of us, then flew down slope and disappeared for a minute or so; it then flew back upslope and perched low in a tree about 15 m from us. I obtained two good images. Bird about the size of a StJa., with a very dark back and, slightly white-tipped, tail. White underneath from forehead and throat, down to bottom of belly. Black nape and crown. Bill smaller than the New World Jays. Dark eye. The birds were silent.There may have been 3 birds.
